.TH "SUBKENNEL" "5" "" "Project Kennel" "File Formats"
.SH NAME
subkennel \- Project Kennel per\-user allocation file
.SH SYNOPSIS
/etc/kennel/subkennel
.SH DESCRIPTION
/etc/kennel/subkennel records, one line per user, the per\-user resources a kennel draws on \(em analogous to /etc/subuid and /etc/subgid. A user with no valid line cannot start \fBkenneld\fR(8). Use \fBkennel subkennel add\fR to append a provably\-valid line and \fBkennel subkennel check\fR to validate the file.
.PP
Each line is colon\-separated: \fIuid\fB:\fItag\fB:\fIgid\fB:\fInamespace\fR. Fields after the fourth are ignored. Blank lines and lines beginning with # are comments.
.SS fields
uid:tag:gid:namespace
.TP
\fBuid\fR \(em decimal
The owning user's uid.
.TP
\fBtag\fR \(em decimal
A per\-user 12\-bit tag (0..4095), unique per uid; partitions the kennel's reserved ranges.
.TP
\fBgid\fR \(em 10 hex digits
The reserved gid base, exactly ten lowercase hex digits.
.TP
\fBnamespace\fR \(em string
The allocation namespace (non\-empty).
.SH FILES
.TP
\fI/etc/kennel/subkennel\fR
The allocation file itself.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
\fBkennel subkennel add \-\-uid 1000\fR
Append a collision\-free allocation for uid 1000.
.TP
\fBkennel subkennel check\fR
Validate every line and report malformed ones.
.SH SEE ALSO
\fBkennel\fR(1), \fBkenneld\fR(8)
